When the context is lost, and starling is not marked to handle it. The "createBuffers" function will crash because it's using a disposed context!

You need to change the code at onContextCreated to this:
        private function onContextCreated(event:Object):void
        {
            var context:Context3D = Starling.context;
            if (context && context.driverInfo != "Disposed")
            {
                createBuffers();
                registerPrograms();
            }
        }

When calling the DisplayObjectContainer.dispose, it will loop over the mChildren and dispose each.
In the child's dispose function it will remove itself from the parent!
This will cause the loop in the DisplayObjectContainer.dispose to go out of bounds. (the children's length is shorter after each call)

This is a fix (Going down the loop, not up):
/*\* Disposes the resources of all children. */
public override function dispose():void
{
    var numChildren:int = mChildren.length;  
    for (var i:int=numChildren-1; i>=0; i--)
    {
        mChildren[i].dispose();
    }
    super.dispose();
}

